{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486672","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486672"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:40:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:40:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"155"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"155","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/155"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.4,0.04,0.12,0.37]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"155"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48282"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"155","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/155"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"155"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33197"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1012"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"2585"},{"type":"tags","id":"2602"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3723"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12973"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48282","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48282"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 36-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a four-day history of increasing shortness of breath and fever. He has a history of intravenous drug use, a 15 pack-year smoking history and drinks one to two beers a week. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears unwell with a pulse rate of 120/min, blood pressure 90/65 mmHg, respiratory rate 25 breaths/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 38.0\u00b0C. He has track marks on his forearms bilaterally and a systolic murmur heard best along the left sternal border. Two sets of blood cultures are sent and an order placed for a transoesophageal echocardiogram. Empirical antibiotic therapy has been started once the blood cultures have been taken.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following complications is the patient most at risk of?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Conjunctival haemorrhages","Pulmonary embolism","Bundle branch block","Atrial fibrillation","Acute heart failure"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical features and intravenous drug use suggest this patient most likely has infective endocarditis with tricuspid valve involvement. \u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary embolism\u003C/strong\u003E in the form of septic pulmonary emboli occurs in up to 75% of patients with tricuspid valve endocarditis, often presenting with dyspnoea, cough, haemoptysis and pleuritic chest pain. This is the most immediate threat for this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute heart failure\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common cause of death in patients with infective endocarditis and usually occurs due to valve insufficiency. However, this complication is more common in left-sided infective endocarditis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConjunctival haemorrhages\u003C/strong\u003E are one of the peripheral phenomena of infective endocarditis, along with Janeway lesions, Osler\u0027s nodes, and splinter haemorrhages. These are less common in right-sided (tricuspid) infective endocarditis, which can make detection more challenging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBundle branch block\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eatrial fibrillation\u003C/strong\u003E are examples of conduction abnormalities and arrhythmias that can occur in infective endocarditis. These are usually caused by the spread of infection to the tissue around the valves, forming paravalvular abscesses. While serious, these complications are less common than pulmonary embolism in tricuspid valve endocarditis. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, while all of these complications can occur in infective endocarditis, septic pulmonary emboli present the most immediate and likely threat in this case of suspected right-sided endocarditis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Septic pulmonary emboli occur in up to 75% of patients with tricuspid infective endocarditis."],"references":["Shmueli et al. Right-Sided Infective Endocarditis 2020: Challenges and Updates in Diagnosis and Treatment. J Am Heart Assoc. 2020 Aug 4;9(15):e017293.","Iftikhar SF, Ahmad F. Tricuspid Valve Endocarditis. [Updated 2022 Jul 5]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK538423/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33197"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"155"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33197","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/33197"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-09T12:48:09+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-07-09T12:48:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"155"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48282"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":